text = "Tuberculosis (TB) is a contagious infectious disease caused by bacteria belonging to the Mycobacterium tuberculosis complex. It primarily affects the lungs but can also involve other parts of the body, such as the kidneys, bones, and central nervous system. TB is an ancient disease, with evidence of its presence found in human remains dating back to ancient Egypt, India, and China. The writings of ancient civilizations, such as the Egyptian Ebers Papyrus (1550 BCE), describe symptoms consistent with TB.

TB is primarily spread through the air when an infected person coughs, sneezes, or talks, releasing droplets containing the bacteria into the air. Inhalation of these infected droplets by others can lead to infection. TB is not easily transmitted through casual contact.

In the 18th and 19th centuries, tuberculosis was often referred to as \"consumption\" due to the way it seemed to consume its victims. It was a leading cause of death during this time period, especially in Europe and North America. Many artists and writers romanticized the disease, associating it with beauty and tragic suffering. The most common symptoms of pulmonary TB (TB in the lungs) include persistent cough (often with sputum or blood), chest pain, fatigue, weight loss, night sweats, and fever. Symptoms of extrapulmonary TB, which affects other parts of the body, vary depending on the affected area but can include pain, swelling, and organ dysfunction.

In the late 19th century, advancements in medical science shed light on the cause and transmission of tuberculosis. In 1882, the German physician Robert Koch discovered the bacterium responsible for TB, Mycobacterium tuberculosis, and established the link between the bacteria and the disease."

