text = "To control the spread of TB, sanatoriums were established in the late 19th and early 20th centuries. These facilities provided a controlled environment for patients, with fresh air, rest, and a healthy diet. Although sanatoriums were not a cure, they offered some relief and improved the chances of recovery for patients.

In 1921, Albert Calmette and Camille Guérin developed the Bacillus Calmette-Guérin (BCG) vaccine, which is still used today as a preventive measure against tuberculosis. The BCG vaccine is most effective in protecting against severe forms of TB in children.

Tuberculosis remains a major global health concern, particularly in developing countries with limited healthcare resources. The emergence of drug-resistant strains, such as multidrug-resistant TB (MDR-TB) and extensively drug-resistant TB (XDR-TB), poses additional challenges to TB control efforts.

International organizations, such as the World Health Organization (WHO), have been working to combat tuberculosis through initiatives like the \"End TB Strategy\" launched in 2015. The goal is to reduce TB deaths by 95% and new cases by 90% by 2035."
